<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-396-154  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 396 154.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The New York Times  July 4 1989 v138 n47,921 p23(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>An editor for business writers. (Rightrighter, computer softwarefrom Rightsoft) (Software Review) (Peripherals) (evaluation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shannon, L.R.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>RightWriter 3.1 ($95), from Rightsoft, is a recommended grammarand spell-checking program intended for business persons, thoughother writers can benefit from it.andP;  RightWriter makes a copy of adocument.andP;  Then, RightWriter checks the copy against 4,500 rulesand a dictionary.andP;  Output consists of the marked up copy togetherwith statistics, such as number of words, and with judgementsabout readability.andP;  The program's rules are of two kinds:noncontroversial, such as noun-verb agreement; and arguable, suchas overuse of a phrase or potentially offensive language.andP;  Rulescan be turned off or modified.andP;  Users can set for educationallevel (general public or general business) or set for type ofwriting (general business, technical, manual, proposal orfiction).andP;  RightWriter runs under MSDOS 2.0 or later and requires384Kbytes.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   RightSoft Inc. (products).andO;Product:   RightWriter 3.1 (Text editor).andO;Topic:     Grammar CritiquingStyle CritiquingWriting SkillsEvaluation.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>